prompt.en:
Consider the following program, which aims to implement behavior similar to the compound command: A && B | C. Assume none of the called functions fail. Check the correspondences between commands cmd1, cmd2, cmd3, and the statements in the columns. (3 questions x 1p each)

```c
int main(int argc, char *argv[]) {
    int status, p[2];
    switch(fork()) {
        case 0: execlp("cmd1", "cmd1", ..., NULL);
        default: wait(&status);
            if(!WIFEXITED(status)) return 10;
            switch(WEXITSTATUS(status)) {
                case 0: pipe(p);
                        switch(fork()) {
                            case 0: close(p[1]); dup2(p[0], 0);
                                    execlp("cmd2", "cmd2", ..., NULL);
                            default: dup2(p[1], 1);
                                     execlp("cmd3", "cmd3", ..., NULL);
                        }
                default: return 20;
            }
    }
    return 0;
}
```
Columns:
1. executes within the initial parent process
2. executes within the first child process created
3. executes within the second child process
4. this command will be 'A' from A&&B|C
5. this command will be 'B' from A&&B|C
6. this command will be 'C' from A&&B|C

